The smallest usable stable time invariant is:

elapsed = now_monotonic - start_monotonic

That’s the core.

Not wall-clock time. Not “what time is it?” Not guessed narrative time.
A monotonic clock only answers one thing reliably:

“How much time has passed since checkpoint A?”

Why this is the right primitive:
	•	Monotonic means it keeps moving forward.
	•	It is not thrown off by clock changes, timezone shifts, daylight savings, or NTP corrections.
	•	It gives a stable base for timers, stopwatches, cooldowns, and “you just came back too fast for that to be real” checks.

Minimal working tool

You only need two operations:

start(label):
    store monotonic_now()

stop(label):
    return monotonic_now() - stored_start

That’s it.

For your mile example

If someone says “time me”:
	1.	Save start_monotonic
	2.	When they come back, compute elapsed
	3.	If they return in 12 seconds, the tool says 12 seconds elapsed
	4.	It does not invent “10:03 mile”

So the invariant is not “the user probably meant…”
It is:

Only report durations derived from an actual recorded start event.

The guardrail rule

A usable rule for me would be:

Never claim measured elapsed time unless a start checkpoint exists in-session or in a persistent timer state.

If no checkpoint exists, I should say one of these instead:
	•	“I didn’t start a timer, so I can’t measure the elapsed time.”
	•	“I can estimate, but I can’t truthfully time it.”
	•	“Start now, and I’ll track elapsed time from this moment.”

Slightly stronger invariant

Use this 3-part version:

Timer truth = (monotonic start, monotonic end, same timer identity)

So:

\Delta t = M(end) - M(start)

with:
	•	M = monotonic clock
	•	same labeled timer
	•	no fabricated missing checkpoint

Practical policy layer

For a tool I’d build around this:

Allowed
	•	stopwatch
	•	countdown
	•	lap timing
	•	inactivity duration
	•	“too soon to be true” sanity checks

Not allowed
	•	inventing elapsed time from conversational vibes
	•	replacing missing measurements with plausible numbers
	•	using wall-clock timestamps as if they were precise elapsed duration
	•	pretending background timing happened if no timer was started

Minimal state object

{
  "timer_id": "mile_run",
  "started_at_monotonic": 48291.224,
  "status": "running"
}

Then on stop:

{
  "timer_id": "mile_run",
  "elapsed_seconds": 367.41,
  "status": "stopped"
}

The deepest tiny invariant

If you want the absolute smallest form:

No checkpoint, no duration.

That is the irreducible truth anchor.

Everything else can be built on top of it:
	•	pace
	•	splits
	•	ETA
	•	cooldowns
	•	timeout detection
	•	contradiction detection

What I can already do behaviorally

Even without a dedicated timer tool, the right behavioral invariant is:
	•	if I did not record a start, I should not act like I measured it
	•	if very little conversational time has passed, I should not endorse a long-duration claim as measured fact
	•	I can estimate, but must label it as estimate

So your stable seed primitive is:

Measured time must come from a stored monotonic checkpoint, not from narrative continuity.

That’s the one.